[recv] {"type": "turn_end", "message": {"role": "assistant", "content": [{"type": "thinking", "thinking": "**Evaluating spring-boot-test inclusion**\n\nI'm contemplating whether to add spring-boot-test for auto-configuration. It's an extra Maven dependency that's useful for the ApplicationContextRunner, but the normal test scaffold might not include it. It feels like if generated tests need Boot's context runner, then including spring-boot-test makes sense. Yet, existing autoconfig modules already add it, possibly due to the agent. Our setup must clearly identify requirements for meaningful coverage. Should we go ahead and include this dependency?\n\n**Investigating dependencies for testing**\n\nI’m looking into resolved artifacts and dependencies, focusing on their normal use and documentation. The setup might be an extra Maven dependency, a Docker image, or an environment property that generated tests need to set. Test utility dependencies could fit well here. I wonder if spring-boot-test or spring-boot-jackson should be included, but I want to avoid being over-prepared. It's possible to instantiate public classes directly without spring-boot-test, but the auto-configuration behavior is only meaningful in Spring context. I'll need to check the documentation for details on auto-configuration for HttpMessageConverters as well.\n\n**Exploring dependencies for coverage**\n\nI’m considering the role of a string customizer and thinking that “meaningful coverage” might relate to JSON message conversion. This leads me to think I should add both spring-boot-jackson and spring-boot-test. The setup here shouldn't be mere guidance, as the driver can apply it before generation. If I add spring-boot-test, tests might need it for the ApplicationContextRunner. However, I’ll need to search for the Spring Boot 4 documentation online for better insights into package requirements.", "thinkingSignature": "{\"id\":\"rs_0904aa2e55e2e353016a41abb37d688196826b53de1b10e355\",\"type\":\"rea